# Chapter 5 - Data Generation in Source Systems

## Definition
A source system is the origin of data used in the data engineering lifecycle.
Data engineers consume data from source systems but rarely own or control them.
Understanding how source systems generate data is the foundation of everything else.

## How Data Is Created
- Analog - speech, writing, instruments converted into digital form
- Digital - natively created by apps, sensors, transactions, and devices
- Every source system has unique patterns, quirks, and characteristics you must learn

## Main Types of Source Systems

### Files and Unstructured Data
- Common formats: CSV, JSON, XML, Excel, TXT
- Files are a universal medium of data exchange
- Many organisations still send and receive data as files

### Application Databases (OLTP)
- Store the current state of an application
- Optimised for fast reads and writes of individual records
- High concurrency, low latency, ACID compliant
- Not suited for large analytical queries

### OLAP Systems
- Optimised for large analytical queries
- Used for data warehouses and reporting
- Opposite of OLTP — scan large volumes, not individual records

### APIs
- REST - most common, stateless HTTP-based data exchange
- GraphQL - flexible queries across multiple data models
- Webhooks - event-based, source pushes data to consumer (reverse API)
- gRPC - Google's efficient bidirectional RPC framework

### Logs
- Capture who, what, and when for every event
- Types: binary (compact), semistructured (JSON), plain text
- Critical for monitoring, debugging, and ML

### Message Queues and Event Streaming
- Message queue - sends discrete messages, delivered once then removed
- Event streaming platform - ordered append-only log, data retained over time
- Examples: Apache Kafka, Amazon SQS, Google Pub/Sub

## Key Database Types to Know

| Database Type | Best For | Examples |
|---|---|---|
| Relational (RDBMS) | Transactional apps, structured data | PostgreSQL, MySQL |
| Key-Value | Caching, session data, fast lookups | Redis, DynamoDB |
| Document | Flexible schema, nested JSON data | MongoDB, Firestore |
| Wide-Column | Massive scale, high write rates | Cassandra, Bigtable |
| Graph | Connected data, relationships | Neo4j, Amazon Neptune |
| Search | Text search, log analysis | Elasticsearch, Solr |
| Time Series | IoT, metrics, sensor data | InfluxDB, Apache Druid |

## Critical Concepts

### ACID
- Atomicity - all or nothing transactions
- Consistency - reads always return the latest written value
- Isolation - concurrent updates do not interfere with each other
- Durability - committed data is never lost

### CDC - Change Data Capture
- Captures every insert, update, and delete event in a database
- Used to replicate data in near real time or create event streams
- Critical for building data pipelines from transactional databases

### CRUD vs Insert-Only
- CRUD - create, read, update, delete — standard app pattern
- Insert-only - never update, always insert a new record with a timestamp
- Insert-only preserves full history but tables grow large over time

### Types of Time
- Event time - when the event actually happened in the source system
- Ingestion time - when the event arrived in your pipeline
- Process time - when the event was transformed or processed
- Always record all three timestamps in your pipelines

## Key Insight
Source systems are usually outside your control but they are your responsibility.
Bad data from source systems causes problems downstream.
Build strong relationships with source system teams, set up data contracts,
and establish SLAs to protect your pipelines from upstream surprises.

## Key Terms I Learned
- OLTP - Online Transaction Processing, optimised for fast individual reads and writes
- OLAP - Online Analytical Processing, optimised for large analytical queries
- CDC - Change Data Capture, tracking every change in a source database
- ACID - database transaction guarantees
- REST - Representational State Transfer, the most common API style
- Webhook - reverse API where the source pushes events to the consumer
- gRPC - Google's efficient remote procedure call framework
- Idempotent - processing a message once produces the same result as processing it many times
- Data contract - written agreement between source system owner and data engineer
- SLA - Service Level Agreement, expectations for system uptime and data quality
- Insert-only - pattern where records are never updated, only new ones are inserted
- Event time - when an event actually occurred in the source system
- Hotspotting - when one partition receives a disproportionate number of messages

